  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Can myopia be cured?",
  "response": "Myopia, or nearsightedness, is a refractive error that causes distant objects to appear blurry while close objects can be seen clearly. While myopia cannot be \"cured\" in the traditional sense, there are several treatment options available that can help manage and correct the condition.\n\n1. **Eyeglasses and Contact Lenses:** The most common and immediate solution for correcting myopia. These refractive tools help to focus light properly onto the retina, thus improving distance vision.\n\n2. **Orthokeratology (Ortho-K):** This involves wearing specially designed rigid contact lenses overnight to temporarily reshape the cornea. The effect lasts during the day, allowing individuals to see clearly without glasses or contacts during waking hours.\n\n3. **Refractive Surgery:** Procedures like LASIK or PRK can reshape the cornea permanently to correct myopia. These surgeries are effective but come with risks and potential side effects, so a thorough evaluation by an eye care professional is necessary.\n\n4. **Phakic Intraocular Lenses (IOLs):** For individuals with high myopia who are not good candidates for laser surgery, implanting an additional lens inside the eye can correct the refractive error.\n\n5. **Atropine Eye Drops:** In some cases, low-dose atropine eye drops have been used to slow the progression of myopia in children, though this is still under research and not universally recommended.\n\nWhile these treatments can significantly improve vision, it's important to have regular eye exams to monitor any changes in your prescription or eye health. If you're considering treatment options, consult with an eye care professional to determine the best approach for your specific situation.",
